  "number": "5.1.11.15",
  "title": "",
  "body": " A small country consists of three states, whose populations are listed below.    A  B  C    6,000  6,000  2,000       If the legislature has 10 seats, use Hamilton's method to apportion the seats.    If the legislature grows to 11 seats, use Hamilton's method to apportion the seats.    Explain what happened in part b. What do you think would be a fair solution?    Try Jefferson's method for 11 seats. Does that solve the problem?         A: 4 seats, B: 4 seats, C: 2 seats    It is not possible to assign 11 seats with Hamilton's method in this case.    States A and C are the same size, so they have the same decimal value. They would both get an additional seat at the same time but there is only one seat to give. Answers will vary on fair solutions.    Yes, with a modified divisor of 1200 we get A: 5 seats, B: 5 seats and C: 1 seat.     "
